  <!-- ═══ WHAT THE MODEL DOESN'T CAPTURE ═══ -->
  <h2>What This Model Doesn't Capture</h2>
  <p>No model is complete. Here's what a DCF inherently misses — and how it might bias our estimate.</p>

  <h3>Upside risks (our number could be too low)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Module adoption:</strong> CrowdStrike frequently upsells existing customers on new modules (Cloud Security, Identity Protection). Accelerating net retention rates could push FCF growth above 20%.</li>
    <li><strong>Operating leverage:</strong> If CRWD drastically cuts sales & marketing spend while maintaining growth, FCF margins could expand from ~27% to 35%+, driving massive value creation.</li>
    <li><strong>M&A synergies:</strong> The company could acquire adjacent security firms and aggressively deploy them through its Falcon platform, compounding growth faster than our organic projections.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Downside risks (our number could be too high)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Stock-Based Compensation (SBC):</strong> Free cash flow ignores the real cost of SBC. If we adjusted FCF to deduct SBC, the true cash flow to shareholders would be significantly lower, cutting the intrinsic value dramatically.</li>
    <li><strong>Competition:</strong> Microsoft (Defender) and Palo Alto Networks are aggressively targeting the endpoint and extended detection and response (XDR) markets. A price war would crush growth and margins.</li>
    <li><strong>Reputational damage:</strong> Any major breach or system failure (like the massive July 2024 global IT outage) inherently damages trust and could lead to churn, breaking the growth assumption.</li>
    <li><strong>Valuation multiples collapse:</strong> The market currently pays a massive premium for CRWD. Even if the company hits these cash flow targets, an overall market re-rating of software multiples could sink the stock price regardless of intrinsic value.</li>
  </ul>

